        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Charleston</placeName>
                <date>15<hi rend="sup">th</hi> April 1851</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I beg as a <hi rend="underline">particular favor</hi> that you
                will<lb/> insert the annexed sketch of <persName>Dr E</persName> in the
                    <date>May</date> Number of<lb/> the Occident, placing it in some conspicuous
                place. If you<lb/>
                <sic>canot</sic> get it in the <date>May</date> No oblige me by forwarding it to
                the<lb/> Editor of the Asmonean, but I should prefer its being<lb/> in your valuable
                Journal. <persName>Dr. E</persName> is opposed by, several<lb/> of his congregation
                who are “tied” hand and foot to <persName>Poznanski</persName> &amp;<lb/> his
                infidel opinions. <persName>Poznanski</persName> though that he could<lb/>
                    mould<add>?</add>
                <persName>Eckman</persName> to his will and make him the promulgator<lb/> of his
                infamous dogmas, but the latter shrunk from the<lb/> contact, and his boldly and
                fearlessly denounced him<lb/> and his infidelity. As an impartial listener I
                have<lb/> given my views thinking they may benefit <persName>Dr. E</persName>
                whom<lb/> I believe to be a truly pious &amp; honest man, his whole<lb/> aim &amp;
                object of life being to benefit his People and in<lb/> endeavoring to make them
                conform to the Holy Religion of their<lb/> Fathers. I shall endeavour to procure
                some of his sermons<lb/> for publication in the Occident, they are replete with<lb/>
                deep devotion, lofty and sublime though, and well<lb/> condensed arguments. If you
                will forward me a Prospectus<lb/> of your Bible I can procure you some subscribers.
                Since<lb/> my return from <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>, a domestic affliction
                has<lb/> prevented me from conforming to the promise made when<lb/> I last saw you,
                viz “that I would write often for the O.”<lb/> I shall do so as often as I can. I
                hope to hear<lb/> of your reinstatement as the spiritual head of the congregation
                “Mikveh<lb/> Israel.” I have been defending you here against the vile<lb/>
                <sic>assersions</sic> of your enemies, among whom you can enumerate<lb/> the
                    <persName>Revd. Jacob Rosenfeld</persName> the applicant for your place who<lb/>
                I suppose has taken <del>up</del> umbrage at the remarks in a previous<lb/> number
                of the Occident. The blow hit hard, and<lb/> “the 'galled Jade <hi rend="underline"
                    >must</hi> wince.”</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>He is beneath your contempt &amp; we shall soon get rid of<lb/> him. So
                    <sic>dont</sic> notice him any more.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I read your address on the presentation of the<lb/> silver with
                great pleasure and satisfaction. Its<lb/> tone was happily conceived, and must have
                touched even<lb/> the obdurate hearts of your detractors &amp; villifiers.</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Wshg<add>?</add> you success &amp; health</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">I remain very truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Your friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">Nathl Levine</persName>
            </p>
            <p><persName>Mrs. L</persName> &amp; family desire their</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">kindest regards to you</p>
